superconsumers_pulse_spotlight.title: 1 in 4 Australians are in the dark about the insurance in their super: Pulse Spotlight

key_findings.finding: 27% of Australians are unsure if they have super insurance or don't know what their policies are.
Over half of 25-29 year olds don't know default insurance starts at age 25.
Australians paid $6.785 billion for group super insurance in 2023-24.
Choice of fund impacts knowledge: 79% in chosen funds knew vs 71% in default funds.
45% of 18-24 year olds don't know if they have insurance or what it is (typically no default insurance in this age group).
Higher knowledge among older people: 84% (55-64) and 88% (65+) know their insurance status.
Gender disparity: 31% of women vs 24% of men don't know their insurance.
Knowledge doesn't significantly change between ages 25 and 54 (28% of 25-34 year olds vs 24% of 45-54 year olds don't know).
Half of those who just reached default insurance age don't know about it.
74% of 18-24 year olds didn't know or got wrong the fact that super funds automatically enroll in default insurance after 25.
Default insurance costs members several hundred dollars annually, potentially more for risky occupations (example: $798 p.a. for a 40-year-old in a dangerous occupation with Cbus).
2018 Productivity Commission found group insurance caused 'excessive' super balance erosion (example: $85,000-$125,000 less retirement income for a low-income blue-collar worker).

recommendations: Productivity Commission review of insurance in super
Examine if insurance in super is the most appropriate method
Analyze net public benefits and costs
Analyze gaps and overlaps with other support schemes
If retained, improve value of insurance in super with standardized terms and consumer protection.

superconsumers_retirement_targets_method.title: Update to Super Consumers Australia Retirement Savings Targets Methodology
superconsumers_retirement_targets_method.purpose: To determine how much superannuation is needed for retirement, providing targets for individuals around ages 55 and 65, considering spending at the 30th, 50th, and 70th percentiles.

methodology_changes.description: Removed multigenerational households from the sample to improve accuracy of expenditure estimations for single and couple households. This addresses the lower shared expenditure among multigenerational households affecting the high-expenditure group.
methodology_changes.reason: The targets are designed for single and couple households only.

changes: Sampling real returns instead of nominal returns.
Sampling monthly returns instead of annual returns (eliminating overlapping periods).
Incorporating historical Australian Bank Bill and Australian Bond returns in the calibrated long-run constructed portfolio real return mean.
Calibration to a historical arithmetic average instead of a geometric average.
methodology_changes.portfolio: 60/40 growth/defensive investment portfolio held from age 65 to 90 (26 years).  Consists of 26.4% Australian Equities, 26.4% World Equities, 7.2% Australian Listed Property, 16% Australian Fixed Interest, 16% World Fixed Interest, 8% Cash.
methodology_changes.simulation: Generates 10,000 paths of 26 years of annual returns by randomly drawing observations from an empirical distribution of historical returns.

changes.description: Lowered the productivity assumption from 1.5% to 1.2% to align with the 2023 Intergenerational Report. This impacts real wage growth and subsequently, Age Pension growth.
Adjusted to account for legislated indexing of the Age Pension, including cost of living increases (LCI/CPI) and a benchmark to male total average weekly earnings (MTAWE).
changes.note: Currently, MTAWE benchmark is below the Age Pension; it will take approximately 10 years to surpass the real Age Pension using LCI/CPI indexing.

superconsumers_retirement_targets_method.acknowledgments: Research Advisory Council and the University of Melbourne Department of Finance provided feedback.
superconsumers_retirement_targets_method.model_development: The model was developed with the assistance of Geoff Warren and Gaurav Khemka from ANU.

standards.description: Covers the basics; mostly met by the Age Pension.
Includes leisure activities, good standard of living (private health insurance, car, household goods, holidays). Assumes partial Age Pension.

generalAdvice.statement: Because everyone's situation is different, it's always best to get advice about tax matters. Contact the Australian Taxation Office (ATO) or a financial adviser.

preRetirementConsiderations.details: Check if you've reached your preservation age.
Review your superannuation balance and potential income streams.
Calculate the tax implications on your retirement income.
Assess eligibility for the capital gains tax retirement concession.
Understand the tax implications of employment termination payments, genuine redundancy payments, and payments from approved early retirement schemes.
Note that tax implications may vary based on reasons for leaving employment (termination, industry change, leaving Australia).

paymentsLeadingToRetirement.details: Tax may be lower than other income; reported as 'Lump sum A' or 'Lump sum B' on income statement.
Tax-free up to a limit based on years of service.
May result in lower tax on payments received.

postRetirementConsiderations.details: Access to seniors and pensioners tax offset, superannuation income stream tax offset.
Eligibility based on disability benefit, death benefit income stream, or age 60 or over.

employeeShareSchemes.goodLeaverConditions: These conditions may allow retention of ESS interests upon retirement.  Risk of forfeiture depends on ESS operation and employee circumstances.

cgtRetirementExemption.details: Capital gains tax retirement concession may exempt up to $500,000 of capital gain on business assets.  No business termination required.  Under 55?  Requires equal personal contribution to superannuation or retirement savings account.

transitionToRetirementRules.description: Allows individuals to reduce working hours without reducing income by starting a Transition to Retirement Income Stream (TRIS) upon reaching preservation age.
transitionToRetirementRules.mechanism: TRIS payments supplement part-time income with regular payments from super savings.
transitionToRetirementRules.accessBeforeChanges: Super access was previously limited to age 65 or retirement.
transitionToRetirementRules.changesFrom2017: Refer to GN 2019/1 for details on changes effective July 1, 2017.
transitionToRetirementRules.accessType: Non-commutable income stream (cannot be converted to a lump sum).
transitionToRetirementRules.lumpSumPayment: Lump sum cash payments are generally not allowed while working.
transitionToRetirementRules.superGuaranteeContributions: Employers must still make compulsory super guarantee contributions for eligible employees, including those on a TRIS.
transitionToRetirementRules.financialAdviceRecommendation: Seek financial advice on super withdrawal options and tax implications.

TRIS_NotRetirementPhase.earningsTaxation: Earnings are taxed at the relevant tax rate and are not eligible for exempt current pension income (ECPI).
TRIS_NotRetirementPhase.transferBalanceCap: Does not count towards the transfer balance cap until it enters the retirement phase.

general.retirementAccess: Access super upon reaching preservation age and retirement.
earlyAccess: Transition to retirement rules (if eligible) while working
general.mandatoryWithdrawal: Not mandatory to cash out upon reaching a certain age. Check super fund rules.

preservationAge.definition: Age to access super; differs from pension age.

taxImplications.taxFree: Super payments may be tax-free at 60 or older.

taxReturn.noReturn: No tax return needed if 60+ and super benefits are only income from a taxed source.
taxReturn.requiredReturn: Tax return required if other income sources exist or PAYG tax withheld from superannuation income stream (including investments or some public sector funds).

recommendations.financialAdvice: Seek financial advice for super withdrawal options, tax implications on retirement, transition to retirement, and superannuation income streams.

earlyRetirementScheme.definition: A payment made by an employer to encourage early retirement or resignation, with a tax-free component up to a certain limit.

taxFreeLimit.basis: Number of years of service with the employer
taxFreeLimit.calculation: Whole dollar amount + amount per year of service

taxation.excessPayment: Treated as an Employment Termination Payment (ETP)

ageLimitChange.after: Extends to individuals 65 and older who retire before pension age

warnings.illegalSchemes: Beware of illegal super schemes promising early access to superannuation.  Heavy penalties apply.
